{"id":"1704.05313","submitter":"Rick Lytel","authors":"Rick Lytel, Sean Mossman, Ethan L. Crowell, and Mark G. Kuzyk","title":"Exact fundamental limits of the first and second hyperpolarizabilities","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Lett. 119, 073902 (2017)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.119.073902","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.optics","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  This letter calculates the exact fundamental limits of the first ({\\beta})\nand second ({\\gamma}) hyperpolarizabilities using Monte-Carlo sampling of\nenergy spectra and transition moments constrained by the diagonal\nThomas-Reiche-Kuhn (TRK) sum rules and filtered by the off-diagonal TRK sum\nrules. The upper bounds of {\\beta} and {\\gamma} are determined from these\nquantities by applying error-refined extrapolation to perfect compliance to the\nsum rules. The method yields the largest diagonal component of the\nhyperpolarizabilities for an arbitrary number of interacting electrons in any\nnumber of dimensions without the necessity for exotic interactions or\nunconventional spectra. The results show that the fundamental limits agree with\nthose achieved by potential optimization and direct solution of mechanical\nHamiltonians, about 30% (40%) below original estimates of the limits for\n{\\beta} ({\\gamma}), and show that the special cases that lead to divergent\nnonlinearities in the many-state catastrophe are not physically realizable.\nThus, this letter shows for the first time that the fundamental limits are\nrigorously exact and are achievable without exotic material designs.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 18 Apr 2017 13:07:38 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 19 Aug 2017 00:39:52 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-08-22"}
